= Introduction

For twenty years, being a software engineer meant one thing: you open an editor, you write code, you ship it. The tools changed — from Vim to VS Code, from SVN to Git, from bare metal to the cloud — but the fundamental loop stayed the same. You, a keyboard, and a problem.

That loop is breaking.

AI agents don't just autocomplete your code. They read your codebase, reason about it, make changes across files, run your tests, and iterate. They're not replacing the editor — they're replacing the _workflow_. The engineer who used to spend 80% of their time typing is now spending 80% of their time thinking, reviewing, and steering.

This is a book about that transition. Not the hype. Not the existential dread. The practical, daily reality of what it means to go from writing software to _engineering_ it — with a crew of agents at your side.

== Why This Book

Because nobody handed us a playbook. The tools showed up fast — Copilot, then Claude, then agents that can run entire tasks autonomously — and we're all figuring it out in real time. Some engineers are thriving. Others are frustrated, skeptical, or quietly terrified.

I wrote this because I needed it myself. A honest look at what's changing, what's staying the same, and how to actually get good at this new way of working.

== Who This Is For

You're a software engineer. You've shipped real things. You know what a production incident feels like at 2am. You're not afraid of the terminal.

But lately, something feels different. Maybe you've tried AI coding tools and found them impressive but chaotic. Maybe you've watched junior engineers ship features faster than you with agent assistance, and it stings a little. Maybe you're excited but don't know where to start.

This book is for you. It assumes you can code. It assumes you've been around. It meets you where you are.

== How to Read This Book

Each chapter is self-contained enough to read on its own, but the book builds a narrative. We start with the shift — what's actually changing and why — then move into the practical: how to work with agents, how to think about code differently, and how to build the judgement that separates a good agentic engineer from someone who just pastes prompts.

Read it front to back, or jump to whatever's bothering you most. Either way works.
